      {
        "id": 2831046,
        "name": "Brad Baker",
        "username": "Brad_Baker",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/brad_baker/{size}/663_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-03-07T01:58:41.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>William,</p>\n<p>I think the 2002 P2 is quite a different wine from the original release.  Personally, I never found the 2002 original release to be a great DP though I know many did.  To me, the shortcomings of the original release show next to the P2.  The original release is currently dominated by the fatness of the year\u2019s over ripe Chardonnay.  This leads it to come across as less focused, more mature, and quite a bit more sweet next to the P2.  In contrast, I find the P2 to have better structure and precision with deeper, darker, and more concentrated flavors highlighted by a salty minerality.  I\u2019ve always found a lot of the Chardonnay from the Cote des Blancs in 2002 to be rather precocious, extra rich, and very fruity.  The original release is showing this character while the P2 manages to find much more balance.  Usually, I prefer a well stored original release to a Late Disgorged/Oenotheque/P2/P3, but I think the 2002 P2 is better right now and will always be.  More a function of the vintage character than anything else.</p>\n<p>I will add that this is definitely going to cellar well and evolve over the next 20-30 years, but no harm in popping one now.  I think it is showing young, but very enjoyable.</p>",
